<h2>How many tablespoons are in a cup?</h2>
<p>
There are 16 tablespoons in one cup.
</p>

<h3>How many tablespoons are in 1/2 cup?</h3>
<p>
There are 8 tablespoons in half a cup.
</p>

<h3>How many tablespoons are in 1/3 cup?</h3>
<p>
There are 5 tablespoons and 1 teaspoon in 1/3 cup. A teaspoon equates to 1/=
3 of a tablespoon.
</p>

<h2>Cup and tablespoon conversions</h2>

<div class=3D"multipleInfoChart">
<table>
 <tbody><tr>
  <th>Cups</th><th>Tablespoons</th><th>Fluid Ounces</th>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td>1 cup</td><td>16 tablespoons</td><td>8 fluid ounces</td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td>3/4 cup</td><td>12 tablespoons</td><td>6 fluid ounces</td>
 </tr>
 <tr>=20
  <td>2/3 cup</td><td>10 tablespoons plus 2 teaspoons</td><td>4 =E2=85=94 f=
luid ounces</td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td>1/2 cup</td><td>8 tablespoons</td><td>4 fluid ounces</td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td>1/3 cup</td><td>5 tablespoons plus 1 teaspoon</td><td>2 =E2=85=93 flu=
id ounces</td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td>1/4 cup</td><td>4 tablespoons</td><td>2 fluid ounces</td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td>1/6 cup</td><td>2 tablespoons plus 2 teaspoons</td><td>1 =E2=85=93 fl=
uid ounce</td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td>1/8 cup</td><td>2 tablespoons</td><td>1 fluid ounce</td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td>1/16 cup</td><td>1 tablespoon</td><td>=C2=BD fluid ounce</td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td colspan=3D"3">1 tablespoon =3D 3 teaspoons</td>
 </tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>

<p>
It's worth noting that usage of the cup in modern recipes is mostly confine=
d to the United States and Canada. The cup hasn't been used as a standard m=
easurement in British recipes since the 1960s. That said, it is still possi=
ble to come across a modern recipe=20
that references a cup of flour, sugar or other ingredient. And the fact tha=
t we're all online these days means your recipe could come from anywhere!=
=20
</p><p>

</p>

<h2>Cups and tablespoons reference chart</h2>
<p>
To make things simple, I've created a reference chart for <b>converting one=
 cup, 1/4 cup, 1/2 cup, 1/3 cup, etc, to tablespoons (and teaspoons)</b> an=
d converting the other way: tablespoons to cups.=20
Please feel free to bookmark it or print it, to keep it handy.=20
</p>

